00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:35.800
Pigeons are part of the Family: Columbidae
and within it there are over 300 species;

00:00:35.800 --> 00:00:37.880
including both pigeons and doves!

00:00:37.880 --> 00:00:39.860
The names are used interchangeably!

00:00:39.860 --> 00:00:44.250
These birds are so successful they've spread
across the entire planet (except the Sahara,

00:00:44.250 --> 00:00:45.809
Antarctic and high Arctic).

00:00:45.809 --> 00:00:48.059
The first mention of them pigeons appeared
in Mesopotamia.

00:00:48.059 --> 00:00:52.030
Ancient humans eventually domesticated them
and kept them for food, just like the chicken.

00:00:52.030 --> 00:00:56.690
Because of their monogamy and two-parent family
units, the dove and pigeon were used in religious

00:00:56.690 --> 00:01:01.940
ceremonies and to represent deities like Ishtar,
Venus, the Holy Spirit, or Aphrodite.

00:01:01.940 --> 00:01:06.420
Once they'd been domesticated, we learned
homing pigeons could be used in bird races

00:01:06.420 --> 00:01:07.860
or to carry messages.

00:01:07.860 --> 00:01:12.000
Europeans brought the rock pigeon with them
to North America where it interbred with the

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:14.799
native pigeon and spread EVERYWHERE.

00:01:14.799 --> 00:01:17.180
That native was the famous Passenger pigeon.

00:01:17.180 --> 00:01:21.600
They were likely the most numerous bird in
the world in the 1800s -- with 136 million

00:01:21.600 --> 00:01:27.210
breeding adults in one site in Wisconsin alone
-- adding up to BILLIONS over the whole country.

00:01:27.210 --> 00:01:31.450
Accounts by Native Americans and European
naturalists say the sky could to turn dark

00:01:31.450 --> 00:01:33.619
for hours while these birds migrated.

00:01:33.619 --> 00:01:39.480
Of course, now the passengers are all extinct
from our hunting and feeding practices, thanks

00:01:39.480 --> 00:01:40.480
humans.

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:45.310
The Rock pigeon we still see in our cities
carries some of its DNA, but it's mainly a

00:01:45.310 --> 00:01:48.360
feral mix of the original European rock pigeon
variety.

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:50.799
These birds are still good for racing and
speed.

00:01:50.799 --> 00:01:54.740
They're adept fliers and evade predators even
in New York City; which is why you rarely

00:01:54.740 --> 00:01:55.860
see dead ones.

00:01:55.860 --> 00:02:01.610
Yes, stray cats get them, but so do the owls,
falcons and hawks that live in Eastern and

00:02:01.610 --> 00:02:05.810
Midwest cities looking for the tasty, juicy,
birds; which breed year-round.

00:02:05.810 --> 00:02:07.130
Even we eat them!

00:02:07.130 --> 00:02:10.119
